\begin_layout Subsubsection
Ultra Wide Band (UWB)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
UWB lies at the lower end of the wireless spectrum that can be used on NoCs.
 This band has been well established in terms of feasibility of implementation
 by various groups, notably by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "4531729"

\end_inset

, who utilize a carrier-free impluse radio-based UWB transciever to design
 a WiNoC.
 The transmitter is designed to generate the desired pulse with suitable
 driving strength so that signal can be efﬁciently radiated from an on-chip
 antenna.
 A CMOS integrated Gaussian monocycle pulse (GMP) generator creates an ultra
 short pulse that yeilds a very low power spectral density.
 The receiver constitutes of a wideband LNA, a correlator, an ADC, and synchroni
zation circuits.
 It employs a 2.98-mm-long meander type dipole antenna that gives 1 mm data
 transmission range, whereas the transceiver can give a sustained data rate
 of 1.16 Gb/s on a channel with central frequency of 3.6 GHz.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
mm Wave
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As per the ITRS, for the 16nm CMOS technology, the cutoff frequency and
 unity maximum available power gain frequency are targetted between 600
 GHz and 1 THz, respectively.
 This level of scaling assists in integrating the WiNoC units on chip as
 the units themselves are expected to scale proportionally.
 This also allows us to explore mm-wave as potential frequency candidate
 in WiNoCs.
 The on-chip antenna should provide us with the best power gain with minimal
 power and area requirements.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "4277869"

\end_inset

 presents a metal zig-zag antenna as one of the most apt candidates for
 the purpose.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "6197727"

\end_inset

 shows that a 0.38-mm antenna can achieve a 3 dB bandwidth of 16 GHz with
 a central frequency of 57.5 GHz.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "O:2005:FOI:1129601.1129739"

\end_inset

 argues that the metal lines over the antenna doesn't affect the the gain
 factor, thus making it compatible with the current fabrication process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
sub-THz Wave
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The minimum antenna size scales down with the wavelength.
 This makes sub-THz region all the more lucrative as it saves real estate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Lee:2009:SMW:1614320.1614345"

\end_inset

 recommends that the antenna be put in a polyimide layer, deposited of the
 top silicon, such that most electromagnetic energy could be conﬁned within
 this low-loss dielectric layer.
 It observes that our primary aim should be to minimize the radiation penetratin
g into the substrate since substrate loss is a major factor in determining
 chip performance.
 The low loss polyimide layer can be shown to constrain most of the signal
 within the layer, boosting the range of communication to a centimeter.
 Since it is possible to switch a CMOS transistor as fast as 500 GHz at
 32 nm CMOS, this allows us to implement a large number of high frequency
 bands for the on-chip wireless network.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "tag:multichannel_lee"

\end_inset

Using a 32 nm CMOS process, empirically, there are expected be total of
 16 available channels, from 100 GHz to 500 GHz, for the on-chip wireless
 network, and each channel can transmit at 10 to 20 Gbps, putting the raw
 aggregate data rate to upto 320 Gbps.
 Again, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Lee:2009:SMW:1614320.1614345"

\end_inset

 predicts that only 1-2% of the power would be used in wireless communication
 with a simple ASK transceiver implementation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
PP
\end_layout

\end_inset

The mm-wave frequency band can provide abundant bandwidth while not suffering
 from severe signal degradation, thanks to the short communication distances
 in the WiNoC.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Lee:2009:SMW:1614320.1614345"

\end_inset

, a noncoherent on–off keying (OOK) based transceiver is designed for an
 mm-wave WiNoC, OOK being selected as it allows relatively simple and low-power
 circuit implementation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
THz Wave
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As observed before, increase in communication frequency is a win-win scenario.
 Antenna characteristics of carbon nanotubes (CNTs) in the THz/optical frequency
 range has been well investigated
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "4420100"

\end_inset

.
 These antennas can achieve a bandwidth of around 500 GHz, whereas antennas
 operating in the millimeter wave range achieve bandwidths of tens of gigahertz.
 A higher frequency-bandwidth translates into a higher data rate.
 Certain specific characteristics of CNTs make them well suited for the
 purpose.
 Extremely low wavelength demands a very thin antenna structure for efficient
 transmission and reception.
 CNTs are naturally just a few nanometers across in diameter, what is virtually
 impossible to acheive using any other fabrication technique.
 Secondly, the virtually defect free CNTs show minimal surface loss and
 thus can detect weak signals very effectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Antennas
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
