\begin_layout Subsubsection
Random
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In random distribution of traffic, every node has a uniform probabibility
 of sending packets to any other node.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So , 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{i,j}=1/n-1\:\forall\: i\neq j$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is probably the most famous distribution and is used in some way or
 other in every model.
 The issue with it is that the uniformity tends to distribute the load pretty
 evenly.
 Thus, even routing algorithms or topologies with poor load balancing acumen
 perform well in this distribution providing misleading benchmark numbers.
 To avoid this, another paradigm of synthetic traffic is used called permutation
 traffic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Permutation traffic
\series default
 is often used to stress a topology/routing algorithm.
 Its primary idea is to generate flows between pairs of nodes.
 So, for a node 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, its destination 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 can be calculated using some given function 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $d=\pi(s)$
\end_inset

.
 These are considered a better parameter to benchmark a topology/routing
 algorithm because they focus on node-node pair traffic which yields more
 realistic distributions than random traffic.
\end_layout

